Basic Algorithm Scripting: Confirm the Ending
Check if a string (first argument, str) ends with the given target string (second argument, target).

This challenge can be solved with the .endsWith() method, which was introduced in ES2015. 
But for the purpose of this challenge, we would like you 
to use one of the JavaScript substring methods instead.


//solution

function confirmEnding(str, target) {
  // "Never give up and good luck will find you."
  // -- Falcor
  //Capture the last string
  //code below works to see about the last char in target
  //  var strTocompare = str[str.length - 1];
  //  if (strTocompare === target) { return true}
  //  else {return false}

  //  Lets start at
  
 // console.log(target.length);
  //console.log(target[target.length -1 ]);
  return str.slice(str.length - target.length) === target;
  
}

confirmEnding("Bastian", "an");
